'''Amberbaken''', or '''Mpur''' (also known as ''Kebar, Ekware,'' and ''Dekwambre''), is a divergent language of New Guinea. It is not closely related to any other language, and though Ross (2005) tentatively assigned it to the [[West Papuan languages]], based on similarities in pronouns, ''Ethnologue'' and ''Glottolog'' list it as a [[language isolate]].<ref name=e21>{{e21|AKC|Amberbaken}}</ref><ref name=Glottolog/> Amberbaken or Mpur has a complex tonal system with 4 lexical tones and an additional contour tone, a compound of two of the lexicals. Its tonal system is somewhat similar to the nearby Austronesian languages of [[Mor language (Austronesian)|Mor]] and [[Ma'ya language|Ma'ya]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Muysken |first=Pieter |date= |title=From Linguistic Areas to Areal Linguistics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n9p4rl09ec0C&pg=PA134&lpg=PA134&dq=tonal+papuan+languages&source=bl&ots=_JtSyxG0Qh&sig=Kj2_na6GEdqwWWG-uEiFhrggsw8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT39qal4PQAhULrVQKHUdgDmYQ6AEILTAB#v=onepage&q=tonal%20papuan%20languages&f=false |location= |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company |page=134 |isbn= 9789027231000}}</ref>
== Phonology == Mpur has five vowels: /a, e, i, o, u/.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" |+Consonants ! colspan="2" | ![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Stop consonant|Stop]] !<small>voiceless</small> |p |t | | |k |- ![[Voice (phonetics)|<small>voiced</small>]] |b |d | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] | | |t͡ʃ | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] |ɸ |s | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m |n | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | |j |w |}
