'''''Conlanging: The Art of Crafting Tongues''''' is a 2017 [[documentary film]] about [[conlang|conlanging]] - the hobby of constructing artificial languages and the people who make them. The film features conlangers [[David J. Peterson]]<ref name=conlangfilm>{{cite web|url=http://conlangingfilm.com/about|title=Conlanging, The Film About|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> ([[Dothraki language|Dothraki]] and [[High Valyrian]] from ''[[Game of Thrones]]''); [[Marc Okrand]]<ref name="conlangfilm"/> ([[Klingon language|Klingon]] from ''[[Star Trek]]'') and [[David Salo]]<ref name=conlangfilm /> (consultant on [[J. R. R. Tolkien|Tolkien]]'s languages, particularly [[Sindarin]] for [[Peter Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' and ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'' movies), as well as [[Paul Frommer]], linguistics professor and creator of [[Na'vi language|Na'vi]]<ref name="660 News">{{cite web |url=http://www.660news.com/2017/07/21/film-looking-creation-languages-premiering-calgary/ |title=Film looking at creation of languages premiering in Calgary|last=Ross |first=Tom |date=21 July 2017 |website=660 News |publisher=Rogers Media |access-date= 30 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref>, and Christine Schreyer, ([[Kryptonian language|Kryptonian]] from [[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]) anthropologist at the [[University of British Columbia]], who hopes to be able to apply conlanging methods to [[endangered languages]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.ok.ubc.ca/2016/07/28/ubc-anthropologist-helps-create-documentary-on-the-art-of-language-construction/ |title=UBC anthropologist helps create documentary on the art of language construction |last=Wellborn |first=Patty |date=28 July 2016 |website=UBC Okanagan News |publisher=[[University of British Columbia]] |access-date= 30 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref> The film also looks at the history of the hobby and modern-day conlangers. While the film was made available for online purchase in 24 August, a [[premiere]] was held on 22 July at the [[University of Calgary]]'s Plaza Theatre.<ref name="660 News"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ucalgary.ca/events/calendar/conlanging-art-crafting-tongues |title=University of Calgary Events: Conlanging: The Art of Crafting Tongues |last= |first= |date=2017 |website=University of Calgary |publisher= |access-date=30 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref>. Production began in 2015, and received funding from the [[Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada]], but the film's future was secured through an [[Indiegogo]] campaign that raised $25,000 during August 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/conlanging-documentary-film-educational#/ |title= Conlanging Documentary Film |last=Watkins |first=Britton |date=2016 |website=Indiegogo |publisher= |access-date= 30 August 2017 |quote=}}</ref> The Language Creation Society provided $3,000 worth of funds towards the film and held an interview with Watkins.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://conlang.org/conlanging-film/ |title=Conlanging film |last= |first= |date=25 July 2016 |website=Language Creation Society |publisher= |access-date= 30 August 2017|quote=}}</ref>
