{{distinguish|Kagoro language (Nigeria)}} {{Infobox language |name=Kita Maninkakan |nativename=Central Malinke |states=Mali |ethnicity=[[Mandinka people|Mandinka]] |speakers=449,000 |date=2001-2014 |ref=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/mwk|title=Maninkakan, Kita|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/xkg|title=Kagoro|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref> |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam1=[[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]] |fam2=[[Mande languages|Mande]] |fam3=Western Mande |fam4=... |fam5=[[Manding languages|Manding]] |fam6=West Manding |minority={{flag|Mali}} |lc1=mwk|ld1=Kita Maninka |lc2=xkg|ld2=Kagoro |glotto=kita1248 |glottorefname=Kita–Kagoro }}
'''Kita Maninkakan''', or '''Central Malinke''', is a [[Manding languages|Manding]] language spoken by close to a million people in [[Mali]], where it is a national language. About 10% are ethnically [[Fula people|Fula]].
The Kagoro variety is 86% lexically similar according to ''Ethnologue'', and is being replaced by [[Bambara language|Bambara]].
