{{Infobox language |name=Kpee |altname=Numu |nativename=''Kpeego'' |states=scattered throughout southwest [[Ivory Coast]] |region= |ethnicity=Kpeera ([[Blacksmiths of western Africa|Numu]]) |speakers=≈ 2,000<!--the ISO change request specifies that this is only an approximate number--> |date=2012 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam1=[[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]] |fam2=[[Mande languages|Mande]] |fam3=Western Mande |fam4=Central |fam5=Manding–Jogo |fam6=Jogo–Jeri |fam7=[[Jogo languages|Jogo]] |iso3=cpo |glotto=kpee1234 |glottorefname=Kpeego }} {{Infobox ethnonym|Kpee|Kpeera|Kpeego}}
The '''Kpee''' language, ''Kpeego'', commonly called '''Numu''' (''Noumoukan''), is a [[Mande languages|Mande language]] spoken by blacksmiths (''[[Blacksmiths of western Africa|numu]]'') in [[Burkina Faso]]. It is thought to be similar to [[Ligbi language|Ligbi]] in Ghana, but no comparison has been done.
