{{Infobox language |name=Unubahe |altname= |region=[[Milne Bay Province]] |state=[[Papua New Guinea]] |speakers=7 fluent |date=2001 survey<!--date of "2012" figures cited by Ethn. 18--> |ref=<ref name=Rueck/> |speakers2=59 total with any ability (2001)<ref name=Rueck/> |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Western Oceanic languages|Western]] |fam5=[[Papuan Tip languages|Papuan Tip]] |fam6=[[Nuclear Papuan Tip languages|Nuclear]] |fam7=[[Suauic languages|Suauic]] |iso3=unu |glotto=unub1234 |glottorefname=Unubahe }}
'''Unubahe''' (Unuba'e) is a nearly extinct [[Oceanic language]] spoken at the southeastern tip of [[Papua New Guinea]]. Although a few children speak it, in 2001 there was only one married couple who both spoke the language.<ref name=Rueck>[http://www.sil.org/pacific/png/abstract.asp?id=928474549168 Rueck, Michael. 2001. ''Unubahe: A nearly extinct language'' (ms)]</ref>
